1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,650
A war has been going on for billions of years 
数十億年も続いている戦争があり

2
00:00:03,650 --> 00:00:08,420
that breeds well armed monsters, who struggle with other monsters for survival. 
武装した怪物たちを生み
生存をかけて戦わせている

3
00:00:08,420 --> 00:00:13,490
Having no particular interest in us, most of them are relatively harmless,
人類に特段の関心はなく
ほとんどは比較的無害だ

4
00:00:13,490 --> 00:00:16,920
as our immune systems deal with their weapons easily. 
免疫系が彼らの武器を
簡単に処理できる

5
00:00:16,920 --> 00:00:19,550
But there are exceptions.
だが、例外もある

6
00:00:19,550 --> 00:00:28,320
Naegleria fowleri is an amoeba that has not only developed a deadly taste for human brains but is also a match for our defences
Naegleria fowleriというアメーバは
人間の脳を食べて死に至らせ、免疫系にも対応する

7
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:31,100
and stars in dramatic headlines. 
劇的な見出しを飾るスターだ

8
00:00:31,100 --> 00:00:35,100
What happens when this monster enters your body?
この怪物が体内に侵入したら
何がおきるのか？

9
00:00:42,940 --> 00:00:45,530
Naegleria fowleri is an amoeba, 
Naegleria fowleriはアメーバだ

10
00:00:45,530 --> 00:00:50,030
a microbe with a nucleus, one of the smallest lifeforms on earth.
核を持つ微生物であり
地球上で最小の生物の一つだ

11
00:00:50,030 --> 00:00:56,850
It is a voracious hunter of bacteria and other critters that it devours whole and rips into pieces.
アメーバは、細菌や他の生物を丸のみして細断する
獰猛なハンターだ

12
00:00:56,850 --> 00:01:02,440
Like many amoebea it is able to transform into different stages that help it survive,
他のアメーバと同様、Naegleria fowleriは
生存のために変形できる

13
00:01:02,440 --> 00:01:06,630
but most of the time Naegleria fowleri is in its trophozoite stage, 
ほとんどの場合、Naegleria fowleriは栄養体で

14
00:01:06,630 --> 00:01:09,630
during which it looks like a squishy blob with tiny arms 
小さな腕を持つグニャグニャの塊で

15
00:01:09,630 --> 00:01:13,130
and hunts, divides and thrives.
それが狩り、分裂し、繁栄している

16
00:01:13,130 --> 00:01:18,380
Its natural home is in fresh water: ponds, rivers, lakes and hot springs. 
本来の生息場所は淡水で
池、川、湖、温水などだが

17
00:01:18,380 --> 00:01:24,320
 But unfortunately it also feels happy in pipes, swimming pools, fountains or spas 
残念ながら、居心地のいい場所には
パイプ、プール、噴水、温泉などもある

18
00:01:24,320 --> 00:01:26,460
when they are not properly treated.
適切な処置が無い場合だ

19
00:01:26,460 --> 00:01:30,140
The warmer the water, the more it thrives and multiplies. 
水温が高いほど
盛んに繁殖していく

20
00:01:30,140 --> 00:01:34,050
So in the summer, when humans seek to cool off and enjoy themselves, 
だから、人間が涼しさと楽しさを求める夏は

21
00:01:34,050 --> 00:01:38,630
the chances are highest that both species will interact.
アメーバと遭遇する可能性が
最大になるのだ

22
00:01:38,630 --> 00:01:40,650
Because this makes it hard to avoid, 
だから回避は難しく

23
00:01:40,650 --> 00:01:45,210
millions of people regularly have contact with the amoeba, especially in warmer climates, 
特に温暖な地域では数百万人が
定期的に接触しており

24
00:01:45,210 --> 00:01:48,320
and many people even seem to have antibodies against it.  
その多くが抗体すら持たないようだ

25
00:01:48,320 --> 00:01:52,790
And this is mostly ok, you can even swallow it without consequences.
まあ概ね問題はなく
水を飲んでさえ感染回避は可能だ

26
00:01:52,790 --> 00:02:00,610
Things turn bad when people dive or swim in water contaminated with the amoeba and water splashes high up into their noses. 
アメーバに汚染された水を泳いだり潜ったりして
水が鼻の高さまでくると、事態は悪化する

27
00:02:00,610 --> 00:02:05,740
In a single drop of lake water there are millions of viruses, bacteria and amoebea
湖の水一滴には何百万という
ウイルス、細菌、アメーバがいるが

28
00:02:05,740 --> 00:02:08,000
and that isn’t really a big deal.
大した問題ではない

29
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:10,910
But Naegleria fowleri is different. 
だがNaegleria fowleriは違う

30
00:02:10,910 --> 00:02:17,160
Let us zoom into the nose of an unsuspecting victim enjoying a great summer day and see what happens.
夏の一日を楽しむ無防備な犠牲者の鼻を拡大し
何が起きるか見てみよう

31
00:02:17,160 --> 00:02:21,980
First of all, the amoeba doesn’t really want to be inside your nose 
第一に、アメーバは望んで
あなたの鼻に入ったのではない

32
00:02:21,980 --> 00:02:26,030
as it is not really looking for trouble, it just wants to eat a few bacteria.  
細菌を少し食べたいだけで

トラブルは求めていないのに

33
00:02:26,030 --> 00:02:29,390
Instead it is greeted by your natural defenses.  
あなたの免疫系に出迎えられる

34
00:02:29,390 --> 00:02:37,530
Unfortunately for humans, Naegleria fowleri happens to be exceptionally good at generally flying under the radar of your immune system.  
困ったことに、Naegleria fowleriはなぜか
免疫系のレーダーを潜り抜けるのが非常にうまい

35
00:02:37,530 --> 00:02:40,810
For example, the inside of your nose is covered by mucosa, 
例えば鼻の内側は
粘膜に覆われ

36
00:02:40,810 --> 00:02:46,430
a slime filled with chemicals that kill or stun possible invaders or alert immune cells.
含まれる化学物質は侵入者を殺すか気絶させ
免疫細胞へ警告する

37
00:02:46,430 --> 00:02:49,830
But Naegleria fowleri is not particularly bothered by them 
だがNaegleria fowleriは特に困らない

38
00:02:49,830 --> 00:02:55,350
and instead calmly checks out the scenery, mildly annoyed about the whole ordeal.
落ち着いて景色を眺めつつ
この試練に少しイラつく程度だ

39
00:02:55,350 --> 00:02:57,470
Now, if you are unlucky,
もしあなたが不運なら

40
00:02:57,470 --> 00:03:02,210
この微生物は
興味をかきたてるものに出会う

41
00:03:02,210 --> 00:03:03,890
: Nerve cells.
神経細胞だ

42
00:03:03,890 --> 00:03:07,970
Your nose is filled with a large network of olfactory nerve cells 
鼻は嗅覚神経細胞の
巨大ネットワークで満ち

43
00:03:07,970 --> 00:03:15,520
that pick up molecules from the outside and transmit their information to your olfactory bulb, the center of smell in your brain.
外界の分子を拾い、その情報を
脳内の嗅覚中枢である嗅球に伝える

44
00:03:15,520 --> 00:03:20,070
To do their job these cells talk to each other by releasing various messenger chemicals 
神経細胞は任務遂行のために
様々な伝達物質を出し

45
00:03:20,070 --> 00:03:23,590
and recognizing them via specific receptors.  
特定の受容体で認識して交流する

46
00:03:23,590 --> 00:03:27,870
One of the most important of these chemicals is acetylcholine.
特に重要な伝達物質が
アセチルコリンだ

47
00:03:27,870 --> 00:03:30,300
Through sheer evolutionary bad luck, 
進化上の不運により

48
00:03:30,300 --> 00:03:35,700
Naegleria fowleri happens to have receptors that recognize acetylcholine.  
Naegleria fowleri は偶然にも
アセチルコリン受容体を持っており

49
00:03:35,700 --> 00:03:41,470
And it seems to attract them irresistibly, a little like moths that are attracted by light.
その伝達物質に強く惹きつけられる

光に蛾が集まるように

50
00:03:41,470 --> 00:03:47,140
So as your olfactory nerve cells do their job, using plenty of acetylcholine to talk to the brain,
嗅覚神経細胞が働くとき
脳への伝達に多量のアセチルコリンが使われ

51
00:03:47,140 --> 00:03:49,680
Naegleria fowleri enters your tissue. 
Naegleria fowleriが
組織に侵入するのだ

52
00:03:49,680 --> 00:03:52,950
It seems to follow the chemical signals upstream.
伝達物質の上昇流を追うように

53
00:03:52,950 --> 00:03:57,560
Neutrophils, crazy suicide warriors begin to attack the amoebae. 
狂気の特攻隊員である好中球が
攻撃を始める

54
00:03:57,560 --> 00:04:00,000
 Individually they have no chance against them 
一対一では勝ち目はない

55
00:04:00,000 --> 00:04:05,600
as the invaders are large and pretty buff fighters, used to dealing with tough enemies. 
アメーバは大型の戦士で
強敵との戦いに馴れているので
（★buffは「研磨」から「手慣れた、熟練の」と解釈しました。そうすると後段と意味が重複するので、結局スルーしています）

56
00:04:05,600 --> 00:04:11,300
 So the defenders swarm the intruders and kill them either by vomiting chemicals that punch holes into them
好中球はアメーバに群がり
身体に穴をあける化学物質を吐いたり

57
00:04:11,300 --> 00:04:15,230
or by literally ripping parts of them off and devouring them. 
身体の一部を切り取って
食い荒らしたりして殺す

58
00:04:15,230 --> 00:04:20,680
But the Naegleria fowleri train is still on track  and while the Neutrophil attacks slow them down, 
だが、好中球の攻撃で遅れても
アメーバは軌道に乗っており

59
00:04:20,680 --> 00:04:24,350
they continue to follow the olfactory nerves to their final destination:
嗅覚神経に沿って
目的地に向かい続ける

60
00:04:24,350 --> 00:04:26,810
Your brain.
あなたの脳だ

61
00:04:26,810 --> 00:04:32,680
This process can take between one and nine days and you’ll probably not notice anything during that time.  
このプロセスには1～9日かかり
その間はたぶん、何も気づかない

62
00:04:32,680 --> 00:04:38,510
Until the amoebae reach the olfactory bulb, the center of smell and entrance to your brain.
嗅覚の中枢であり、脳の入り口である嗅球に
たどり着くまでの間だ

63
00:04:38,510 --> 00:04:41,340
Your brain cells are nothing more than helpless victims 
あなたの脳は無力な犠牲者であり

64
00:04:41,340 --> 00:04:45,770
and they all release that wonderful acetylcholine.
魅力的なアセチルコリンを
わざわざ放出している

65
00:04:45,770 --> 00:04:52,290
Naegleria fowleri initiates a massacre and releases an onslaught of various attack molecules.  
Naegleria fowleriは大虐殺を始め
様々な攻撃分子を猛烈に放出する

66
00:04:52,290 --> 00:04:58,930
Some of them are basically little bombs that rip holes into your cells on contact so their pieces can be eagerly consumed. 
分子の一部は、接触した細胞に穴を空ける小型爆弾で
破片にむしゃぶりつける

67
00:04:58,930 --> 00:05:04,390
But Naegleria fowleri is now multiplying - and it's also becoming really creepy. 
ここで、このアメーバは増殖を始め
いよいよバケモノじみていく

68
00:05:04,390 --> 00:05:11,160
 In a feeding frenzy it can develop up to a dozen suckers called food cups, that look like giant eerie mouths. 
食欲が暴走し、フードカップが1ダースも作られる
巨大で不気味な、口のような吸盤だ

69
00:05:11,160 --> 00:05:18,240
The amoebae engage your brain cells, suck them in and rip large “bites” out of them while they are still alive. 
アメーバはあなたの生きた脳にとりつき
吸い込み、嚙みちぎっていく 

70
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:23,410
Now things escalate quickly and the disease that will kill you sets in.
事態は急速にエスカレートし
死に至る病が発祥する

71
00:05:23,410 --> 00:05:31,810
Alerted by the massacre, millions of immune cells, Neutrophils, Eosinophils and microglias invade the infected tissue. 
大虐殺を受け、好中球、好酸球、ミクログリアが
何百万と感染組織に侵入する

72
00:05:31,810 --> 00:05:37,490
 Which is a problem: your immune system is dangerous and not exactly a careful fighter. 
問題は、免疫系は本来危険なもので
慎重には戦わないことだ

73
00:05:37,490 --> 00:05:41,630
It's like burning down a forest to kill the wolves inside it
森の中の狼を殺すのに
森を焼き払うようなもので

74
00:05:41,630 --> 00:05:44,360
 A really bad idea in the brain.
脳においては最悪の発想だ

75
00:05:44,360 --> 00:05:51,810
They waste no time and attack the amoeba, using all the weapons available to them, from chemicals to trying to eat them alive. 
ただちに免疫系は攻撃を始める
化学兵器から直接の捕食まで、あらゆる手段でだ

76
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:56,660
Neutrophils explode themselves to erect barriers spiked with deadly chemicals. 
好中球は自爆し
致死的な化学兵器を含むバリアを張る

77
00:05:56,660 --> 00:05:58,590
A fierce battle ensues.
壮絶な戦闘だ

78
00:05:58,590 --> 00:06:04,830
Naegleria fowleri can actually fight back, itself attacking and killing many immune cells.
Naegleria fowleriも反撃でき
多くの免疫細胞を攻撃し死滅させる

79
00:06:04,830 --> 00:06:09,580
The immune system now throws everything it has at the invader but in vain.
免疫系は全てを侵略者にぶつけるが
無駄に終わる 

80
00:06:09,580 --> 00:06:15,310
The complement system, tiny protein bombs that can kill intruders on their own, are easily disabled. 

侵入者を殺せる小さなタンパク爆弾
「補体系」も容易に無効化される
★1行目が補体系の説明であるというのが何か伝わりづらい気がして、カギカッコをつけました。

81
00:06:15,310 --> 00:06:20,020
Antibodies, usually one of your superweapons, are just destroyed or swallowed. 
超兵器のはずの抗体も
ただ壊されるか飲み込まれる

82
00:06:20,020 --> 00:06:23,330
A high fever that usually slows enemies down does nothing, 
侵入者を鈍らせる高熱も無意味だ

83
00:06:23,330 --> 00:06:26,500
as the amoeba actually thrives in the heat. 
高温で繁栄しているのだから

84
00:06:26,500 --> 00:06:32,270
All the while the amoebae continue to multiply, fight and devour your brain cells. 
その間もアメーバは増殖し、戦い続け
あなたの脳に齧り付いていく

85
00:06:32,270 --> 00:06:35,660
A disastrous chain reaction is taking place.  
悲惨な連鎖反応が生じる

86
00:06:35,660 --> 00:06:40,420
One major thing your immune cells do when they fight is to cause inflammation.
戦闘モードの免疫細胞は
炎症を生じさせる

87
00:06:40,420 --> 00:06:45,150
Which directs large amounts of fluid from your bloodstream into the site of an infection.  
その結果、血管から大量の体液が
感染部位に流れ込む

88
00:06:45,150 --> 00:06:50,590
So as the battle rages on without a clear winner, more and more fluid enters the brain.
決着が遅れるほど
さらに体液が脳に流れ込んでいくのだ

89
00:06:50,590 --> 00:06:54,630
At this point the human will feel symptoms that quickly escalate.  
ここで人間は
症状の急激な加速を感じる

90
00:06:54,630 --> 00:06:59,900
It all begins pretty vaguely, a headache, fever, nausea and vomiting. 
まずは漠然とした症状の
頭痛、発熱、吐き気、嘔吐から始まり

91
00:06:59,900 --> 00:07:03,680
 As the battle spreads rapidly through the brain serious symptoms appear, 
脳内の戦闘が激化すると
症状も深刻化する

92
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:09,840
from confusion, inability to concentrate to fatigue, seizures and hallucinations.  
混乱、集中力の欠如、疲労、発作、幻覚などだ

93
00:07:09,840 --> 00:07:14,910
The brain swells up massively but can’t expand due to the bones surrounding it. 
脳は強く膨張するが
頭蓋に囲まれ広がれないため

94
00:07:14,910 --> 00:07:19,870
So it compresses and disables the brainstem that controls things like breathing.
呼吸などを制御する脳幹が
圧迫され機能しなくなる

95
00:07:19,870 --> 00:07:23,730
Usually within a week the patient dies.
通常、1週間以内に
患者は死亡する

96
00:07:23,730 --> 00:07:28,770
Up to 97% of patients infected by the amoeba share this fate. 
このアメーバの感染者の97％が
同じ運命をたどる

97
00:07:28,770 --> 00:07:33,310
 In almost all cases, by the time an infection by Naegleria fowleri is recognized 
ほぼ全てのケースで
感染に気付くころには

98
00:07:33,310 --> 00:07:38,530
 the disastrous battle for the brain is already so far along that there is almost nothing to be done.
すでに脳内は苛烈な戦闘中で
手遅れなことがほとんどだ

99
00:07:38,530 --> 00:07:41,670
Not only do we currently not have effective treatments,
有効な治療法が無いばかりか

100
00:07:41,670 --> 00:07:44,130
there are also an abundance of open questions 
未解決の謎が山積している

101
00:07:44,130 --> 00:07:51,720
about how an amoeba that usually enjoys its life in open water, is able to overcome our immune system so effectively.
淡水で生活するアメーバが
人間の免疫系に見事に対処できる理由についてだ

102
00:07:51,720 --> 00:07:56,910
So how worried do you need to be about this horrifying killer amoeba?
では、この恐るべき殺人アメーバを
どれだけ警戒すべきか！？

103
00:07:56,910 --> 00:07:58,580
Well, not very. 
まあ、そんなに

104
00:07:58,580 --> 00:08:03,600
While the Naegleria fowleri is clearly extremely deadly and the infection truly horrible,
Naegleria fowleri は明らかに極めて致死的だし
感染は真の恐怖だが

105
00:08:03,600 --> 00:08:07,330
there have only been a few hundred cases in the last few decades.
過去数十年で数百件の報告しかない

106
00:08:07,330 --> 00:08:11,650
You are way more likely to drown in a pool than to get infected. 
プールで感染するより
溺れる可能性の方が高い

107
00:08:11,650 --> 00:08:14,770
Not only does the amoeba need to be flushed high up your nose,
鼻の深くに付着するだけでなく

108
00:08:14,770 --> 00:08:20,220
it also needs to get a good grip and it also has to make its way through the first lines of your defences.
しっかり掴まり
防御の第一線を通過する必要もある

109
00:08:20,220 --> 00:08:26,050
Ultimately Naegleria fowleri is neither evil nor a huge public health risk.
結局、Naegleria fowleriは
悪魔でも公衆衛生上の巨大リスクでもない

110
00:08:26,050 --> 00:08:29,870
But every year some unlucky people have to deal with it. 
ただ毎年、不幸な人々が
相手をさせられている

111
00:08:29,870 --> 00:08:31,950
 We still have so much to learn about it 
解明すべき点は多く

112
00:08:31,950 --> 00:08:34,020
and until we find a way to treat it,
治療法を見つけるまでは

113
00:08:34,020 --> 00:08:42,080
Naegleria fowleri will continue to be this vague and horrifying thing, hunting in puddles and lakes and sometimes pools. 
Naegleria fowleri は水たまりや池、
たまにプールにいる脅威の怪物のままだ

114
00:08:42,080 --> 00:08:49,060
Usually for bacteria. And very occasionally, for people.
基本的には細菌への脅威だが
極めて稀に、人間に牙をむくのだ

115
00:08:50,470 --> 00:08:53,820
- Oh hey, who are you?
「あれ、あなたは誰？」

116
00:08:53,820 --> 00:08:57,390
It is me, your existential dread!
「俺だよ、お前の実存的恐怖だよ」

117
00:08:57,390 --> 00:08:59,250
- Uhm, ok.
「ふーん、そう」

118
00:08:59,250 --> 00:09:04,230
I'm here to make you question your own existence and everything you hold dear in life!
「お前の実存や、大切なもの全てに
疑念を抱かせてやろう」

119
00:09:04,230 --> 00:09:05,400
- Could you not please.
「やめておくれ」

120
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:06,880
Tooooooo late,
「手遅れだ！」

121
00:09:06,880 --> 00:09:14,100
 just look at all these amazing posters FULL of humbling visualisations like the scale of the universe.
「この素晴らしい視覚化ポスターの数々を見ろ
宇宙スケールのやつなんて屈辱的だ」

122
00:09:14,100 --> 00:09:18,860
LOOK! How huge it is and how small you are! 
「見ろ、宇宙がいかに大きく
お前がどれだけ小さいかを！」

